"Valiente A.G., Juanes F., Garcia-Vazquez E.","Increasing regional temperatures associated with delays in atlantic salmon sea-run timing at the southern edge of the European distribution",2011,"Transactions of the American Fisheries Society","140","2",,"367","373",,,10.1080/00028487.2011.557018,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84860526637&partnerID=40&md5=94a87d61f69473522b6ce15cd12b9cc7","Departamento Biologia Funcional, Universidad de Oviedo, C/Julian Claveria s/n, Oviedo 33006, Spain; Department of Natural Resources Conservation, University of Massachusetts, Amherst MA 01003, United States; Departamento Biolog ́ia Funcional, Universidad de Oviedo, C/Julian Claveria s/n, Oviedo 33006, Spain","Valiente, A.G., Departamento Biologia Funcional, Universidad de Oviedo, C/Julian Claveria s/n, Oviedo 33006, Spain; Juanes, F., Department of Natural Resources Conservation, University of Massachusetts, Amherst MA 01003, United States; Garcia-Vazquez, E., Departamento Biolog ́ia Funcional, Universidad de Oviedo, C/Julian Claveria s/n, Oviedo 33006, Spain","Populations of Atlantic salmon Salmo salar at the edge of the species' distribution are the most vulnerable to environmental changes. Those inhabiting southern European rivers are expected to be particularly affected by global warming. However, they are exploited as a very valuable resource for the region, attracting tourism and generating substantial income. In the central part of northern Spain (Asturias), there is a long tradition of sport fisheries (angling). The first salmon caught in a river each year is called the ""campanu."" Analysis of a 50-year time series demonstrates that the run timing of the Asturian Atlantic salmon has changed over this period, as inferred from significant delays in the date of capture of the campanu. Average campanu weight has experienced a parallel significant decrease but age has not changed, indicating diminution of salmon condition. These changes are statistically associated with an increase in regional temperature, there being a minor effect of the global climate North Atlantic Oscillation index. Negative effects of high temperatures on salmon run and feeding, together with long migratory routes, may explain these results. © American Fisheries Society 2011.",,"angling; global climate; global warming; mariculture; migration route; North Atlantic Oscillation; salmonid fishery; spatial distribution; sport fishing; time series; Spain; Salmo salar",,,,,,"Ayllon, F., Martinez, J.L., Garcia-Vazquez, E., Loss of regional population structure in Atlantic salmon, Salmo salar L., following stocking (2006) ICES (International Council for the Exploration of the Sea) Journal of Marine Science, 63, pp. 1269-1273; Baglinière, J.L., Age determination by means of scales for Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar) in the southern part of their distribution: Practical applications and difficulties with the method (1985) Bulletin Français de la Pêche et la Pisciculture, 298, pp. 69-105; Both, C., Visser, M.E., Adjustment to climate change is constrained by arrival date in a long-distance migrant bird (2001) Nature (London), 411, pp. 296-298; Braña, F., Nicieza, A.G., Garrido, R., Vauclin, V., Characterization of Cantabrian populationis of Atlantic salmon and analysis of variation in catches and age structure (1995) Biología y conservaci ón del salmón atlántico (Salmo salar) en los ríos de la región cantábrica, pp. 27-65. , in F. Braña, editor, [Biology and conservation of Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar) in the rivers of the Cantabrian region.] Institute of Conservation ofNature (ICONA). Madrid; Buch, E., Ecosystem variability in West Greenland waters (2004) Journal of Northwest Atlantic Fisheries Society, 34, pp. 13-28; Carr, J.W., Anderson, J.M., Whoriskey, F.G., Dilworth, T., The occurrence and spawning of cultured Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar) in a Canadian river (1997) ICES Journal of Marine Science, 54, pp. 1064-1073; Croxall, J.P., Trathan, P.N., Murphy,